      "script": "In today’s lecture, we’ll explore the paradox of modern work. Many employees take pride in the goods and services they produce, yet they often feel they have little control over their daily tasks. This lack of autonomy contributes to a growing sense of being time-poor—a feeling that there are never enough hours in the day. Studies show this time scarcity is more damaging to well-being than even rising economic inequality or declining productivity. Meanwhile, technological advancements are reshaping the workplace. While some fear that automation puts jobs and wages at risk, others argue it liberates people from tedious labor and creates new opportunities in IT. But the deeper question remains: how do we find meaning in work? Is it through pursuing purpose in our careers, or by prioritizing life outside the office? Perhaps the key lies not in the workplace alone but in strengthening community relationships and realizing our social value beyond the job. These are the tensions we must address as we rethink the future of work.",
