      "id": "p8b2",
      "script": "In today's lecture, we explore the pitfalls of modern ambition. Many people fall into the trap of what we call \"mindless acquisition\"—being driven not by purpose, but by an endless desire for more material possessions. This constant chase often isolates us from our fellow beings, as we become so focused on personal gain that we neglect relationships and community. The real danger is not just loneliness; it's developing an incorrect sense of well-being, mistaking wealth for happiness.\n\nSo how should we set our life goals? Contrary to popular belief, they shouldn't be based solely on theoretical concepts or even personal interests. True fulfillment comes when we include goals that help other people. This outward focus increases our sense of worthiness and connects us to something larger than ourselves.\n\nFinally, what is the worst outcome of a misguided life? Perhaps it is not giving up the chance to fulfill yourself, but something more subtle—drifting through life aimlessly. Without clear, meaningful goals, we abandon all that life has to offer, and eventually, we risk spoiling our character and integrity. So ask yourself: Are you driving your life, or are you just being driven?",
