      "id": "p11l1",
      "script": "Today we explore how conflict resolution, biodiversity crisis, and human identity converge on one insight: we are deeply interconnected. Effective conflict strategies are learned, not innate—the key is understanding the other side’s specific expectations. The wise approach, like the owl, values both goals and relationships, unlike the aggressive shark or avoidant turtle.\n\nNow consider our planet. Earth has entered its sixth mass extinction, with species vanishing at alarming rates. Yet one project dwarfs all other conservation efforts: DNA barcoding. This international collaboration aims to catalogue every species, helping save them from extinction and boosting human health. It is the most exciting, timely, and inspirational scientific endeavour ever undertaken.\n\nFinally, think of human individuality. The notion that we are separate, self-sufficient beings is a delusion—one rooted in the 17th century mindset, not reality. John Donne’s famous line “no man is an island” reminds us we are part of a bigger world. By embracing this awareness, we can see how disruptive our problems have become and work together persistently. Only then can we truly address global challenges.",
