      "script": "(lecture) Many parents today worry excessively about the physical risks involved in adventure sports for their children. While safety is certainly important, this overprotectiveness often does more harm than good. For one thing, adventure sports like rock climbing, kayaking, or mountain biking bring greater benefits to young people precisely because they require facing real challenges. When parents impose too many rules or pressures, they may actually make these activities less suitable for young people. More importantly, the constant safety rules and parental fears prevent kids from enjoying the very essence of adventure sports. By eliminating all perceived dangers, parents rob their children of the chance to cultivate courage—the kind that comes from managing risk rather than avoiding it entirely. Similarly, team-based adventure sports teach young people how to cooperate and support each other; if kids are never allowed to participate, they miss the opportunity to develop team spirit. However, this doesn't mean we should send children into dangerous situations unprepared. A better approach is to introduce them to these sports step by step, starting with controlled environments and gradually increasing challenge levels as they gain skill and confidence. We can also encourage them to take up these sports when they are more mature, but we should never completely deprive them of the valuable lessons that only adventure sports can teach.",
