      "script": "For centuries, people have tried to detect lies through theorization—constructing elaborate psychological models. However, research suggests that generalized rules about liars often fail. In fact, most deceptive signals are not easy to detect; they're subtle and easily masked. Moreover, many lies are well intended, told to protect feelings rather than to harm. So how do we actually catch deceit? Studies show it's mostly by chance, not through any systematic observation or conversation strategy. While some claim objectivity, the truth is that casual encounters reveal more than structured interviews. What specific techniques work? Looking the speaker in the eye is commonly recommended, but it can be misleading. Listening carefully to the speaker’s words often provides better clues than visual cues. Measuring the speaker’s breathing rate is another method, though it requires equipment. Focusing on the speaker’s facial expressions remains popular, yet micro-expressions are fleeting. The key is combining multiple approaches rather than relying on any single sign.",
