      "id": "p28c1",
      "script": "In psychology, we often distinguish between two types of decision-makers: maximizers and satisficers. Maximizers are those who always seek the absolute best. They are often perceived as ambitious, but also as arrogant and sometimes toxic in their relentless pursuit. They can think big and break conventions, but they struggle with satisfaction. In contrast, satisficers tend to air their views more openly and work flexible hours, but they don’t necessarily aim for perfection.  \n\nOne key idea here is that the maximizer mindset actually enables people to learn and grow, though it can also alter their mindsets in unhealthy ways. Consider a traveler I once interviewed. He spent his entire vacation constantly looking for the best place to stay, checking reviews and moving hotels. He never had a great time sightseeing or relaxing because he was so focused on optimizing. Instead of visiting a different city each day, he ended up stuck in one place, dissatisfied.  \n\nSo, what should we do? The research suggests we should prioritize what is essential to our best advantage rather than stretch out the process in search of the optimal. Time pressure often helps us make faster decisions, but modern technology can overwhelm us with too many options. The best strategy is to research as many different options as possible, then focus on what is practical rather than endlessly deliberating.",
