      "script": "Today's lecture examines three fascinating topics. First, a study on emotions challenged the traditional view that simply classified feelings as positive or negative. Researchers found this approach overlooked the fact that emotions are personal and subjective, and that people can control their emotional responses. They measured positive and negative emotions independently, discovering that solitude had a surprising effect: sitting alone for 15 minutes made participants restless, but it actually reduced high-arousal emotions like excitement or anxiety, while increasing low-arousal emotions like calmness. Solitude seemed to go hand in hand with sadness for some, but overall it helped people down-regulate intense feelings rather than intensify negative ones.\n\nSecond, let's talk about brain energy consumption. Many assume deep thinking uses the most energy, but actually the brain consumes almost a quarter of the body's total energy even at rest. Much of this consumption has nothing to do with conscious activities—it's for background maintenance. When we perform difficult cognitive tasks, energy usage devoted to active learning accounts for only a small part. Interestingly, the brain's energy supply is believed to remain basically constant, so mental exhaustion isn't really about running out of fuel.\n\nFinally, consider the common interview question \"Tell me about yourself.\" Job seekers often feel at a loss where to start because it's so open-ended. Career coaches advise taking control of your narrative rather than just repeating resume points. To prepare, candidates should identify a broad general strength to elaborate on, produce examples for different interview questions, and reflect on past achievements and failures. Also crucial is figuring out why the company provides the job opening—this helps tailor your answers to the company's long-term goals.",
