      "script": "W: Today, we're going to explore how our emotions influence our physical well-being. Consider this: every time you experience strong joy or sudden anger, your body chemistry changes almost instantly. Hormones and neurotransmitters flood your system, creating a cascade of physiological responses. But here's the fascinating part—these emotional states don't just pass; they often linger, returning to you unexpectedly. A memory can trigger the same chemical reaction days or weeks later. This leaves a long-lasting impression on your mind, gradually shaping your thought patterns and even your personality. Now, think about what we often mistakenly pursue. Many people strive for success while feeling irritated, believing achievement can override negative emotions. Others chase happiness while neglecting their health, as if good moods could exist independently. The truth is, you cannot sustain success or happiness when your body is in constant distress. Frustration and failure are inevitable, but learning to navigate them without letting your health deteriorate is key. Ultimately, your physical state and emotional state are not separate—they are closely connected. One directly influences the other, constantly reinforcing each other. So, the next time you feel dark moods creeping in, remember: your body is listening.",
