      "script": "Let's begin today's lecture with a look at invasive species. Contrary to popular belief, not all non-native species cause harm. In fact, many contribute to regional biodiversity. However, some do pose a threat to local ecosystems. Scientists now argue that the traditional classification of species as native or non-native is overly simplistic. In reality, these distinctions are artificial because species interactions are constantly evolving. Research shows that only a few introduced species actually cause problems; most either fail to survive or integrate harmlessly. And about 10 percent become naturalized, sometimes even benefiting their new environments.\n\nNow, let's turn to cross-cultural business practices. When dealing with international clients, it's essential to research their specific demands and adopt the right strategies. For example, in some cultures, showing your palm is considered rude, while clicking your fingers loudly in someone's presence is deeply offensive. Gift-giving also requires care; avoid items of great value as they may cause embarrassment. These clients tend to be friendly and enthusiastic, but they have a strong sense of worth and value respect above all. Note their daily schedule—they typically take a break from 2:00 to 5:30 p.m.\n\nFinally, consider the transformation of Reader's Digest under George Grune. He completely changed the company's culture. He believed the magazine's articles should be short and inspiring, appealing to both blue- and pink-collar workers. During his tenure, several hundred employees were fired as part of a major restructuring. Yet he was known to treat employees like members of his family, a reflection of his years as a church minister. Under his leadership, the magazine's subscriptions increased considerably, and he had the boardroom extensively renovated, filling it with paintings by world-famous artists. His strategy proved that a magazine can be both profitable and principled.",
